  1384→/* Try a partial resynchronization with the master if we are about to reconnect.
  1385→ * If there is no cached master structure, at least try to issue a
  1386→ * "PSYNC ? -1" command in order to trigger a full resync using the PSYNC
  1387→ * command in order to obtain the master run id and the master replication
  1388→ * global offset.
  1389→ *
  1390→ * This function is designed to be called from syncWithMaster(), so the
  1391→ * following assumptions are made:
  1392→ *
  1393→ * 1) We pass the function an already connected socket "fd".
  1394→ * 2) This function does not close the file descriptor "fd". However in case
  1395→ *    of successful partial resynchronization, the function will reuse
  1396→ *    'fd' as file descriptor of the server.master client structure.
  1397→ *
  1398→ * The function is split in two halves: if read_reply is 0, the function
  1399→ * writes the PSYNC command on the socket, and a new function call is
  1400→ * needed, with read_reply set to 1, in order to read the reply of the
  1401→ * command. This is useful in order to support non blocking operations, so
  1402→ * that we write, return into the event loop, and read when there are data.
  1403→ *
  1404→ * When read_reply is 0 the function returns PSYNC_WRITE_ERR if there
  1405→ * was a write error, or PSYNC_WAIT_REPLY to signal we need another call
  1406→ * with read_reply set to 1. However even when read_reply is set to 1
  1407→ * the function may return PSYNC_WAIT_REPLY again to signal there were
  1408→ * insufficient data to read to complete its work. We should re-enter
  1409→ * into the event loop and wait in such a case.
  1410→ *
  1411→ * The function returns:
  1412→ *
  1413→ * PSYNC_CONTINUE: If the PSYNC command succeeded and we can continue.
  1414→ * PSYNC_FULLRESYNC: If PSYNC is supported but a full resync is needed.
  1415→ *                   In this case the master run_id and global replication
  1416→ *                   offset is saved.
  1417→ * PSYNC_NOT_SUPPORTED: If the server does not understand PSYNC at all and
  1418→ *                      the caller should fall back to SYNC.
  1419→ * PSYNC_WRITE_ERROR: There was an error writing the command to the socket.
  1420→ * PSYNC_WAIT_REPLY: Call again the function with read_reply set to 1.
  1421→ * PSYNC_TRY_LATER: Master is currently in a transient error condition.
  1422→ *
  1423→ * Notable side effects:
  1424→ *
  1425→ * 1) As a side effect of the function call the function removes the readable
  1426→ *    event handler from "fd", unless the return value is PSYNC_WAIT_REPLY.
  1427→ * 2) server.master_initial_offset is set to the right value according
  1428→ *    to the master reply. This will be used to populate the 'server.master'
  1429→ *    structure replication offset.
  1430→ */
  1431→
  1432→#define PSYNC_WRITE_ERROR 0
  1433→#define PSYNC_WAIT_REPLY 1
  1434→#define PSYNC_CONTINUE 2
  1435→#define PSYNC_FULLRESYNC 3
  1436→#define PSYNC_NOT_SUPPORTED 4
  1437→#define PSYNC_TRY_LATER 5
  1438→int slaveTryPartialResynchronization(int fd, int read_reply) {
  1439→    char *psync_replid;
  1440→    char psync_offset[32];
  1441→    sds reply;
  1442→
  1443→    /* Writing half */
  1444→    if (!read_reply) {
  1445→        /* Initially set master_initial_offset to -1 to mark the current
  1446→         * master run_id and offset as not valid. Later if we'll be able to do
  1447→         * a FULL resync using the PSYNC command we'll set the offset at the
  1448→         * right value, so that this information will be propagated to the
  1449→         * client structure representing the master into server.master. */
  1450→        server.master_initial_offset = -1;
  1451→
  1452→        if (server.cached_master) {
  1453→            psync_replid = server.cached_master->replid;
  1454→            snprintf(psync_offset,sizeof(psync_offset),"%lld", server.cached_master->reploff+1);
  1455→            serverLog(LL_NOTICE,"Trying a partial resynchronization (request %s:%s).", psync_replid, psync_offset);
  1456→        } else {
